I owe the Chainbreakers everything. One day, I’ll repay them with more than gratitude.
Freedom isn’t easy. It’s confusing, messy, frightening. But it’s right.

I’m still scared the guards will drag me back. But each day that fear shrinks a little.

The Chainbreakers didn’t just save my life. They gave it back to me.
Freedom tastes strange some days. Sweet, bitter, overwhelming. But it’s mine now.

Russ told me my name matters. I’m still learning how to say it without whispering.
I’m not strong yet. But I’m getting there. Every sunrise adds a little more.
I used to count the days of work. Now I count the days of freedom. I think I’ll lose track soon.

I still can’t believe Russ kicked down the cell door himself. Thought I was dreaming until the dust hit my eyes.
When he pulled me out of that cell, I could barely walk. Russ carried me without a word. That silence healed something in me.
Every time I hear keys jingle, I remember that last guard whose ring Russ took. The sound means freedom now.
I have nightmares of the prison, but wake with the memory of Russ pulling me into the night air. That memory wins.
They locked me away for speaking up. Russ said I should never stop. I’m learning to raise my voice again.
The Chainbreakers call it a rescue. I call it rebirth.
Russ told me to keep moving, not look back. I try to live my life the same way now.
I’ll never forget the way the moonlight hit his face when he said I was safe. It felt like the sky agreed.
If Russ ever calls, I’ll be there. He saved my life. Now it belongs to freedom.
Pasha Anidani’s prison stank of mold and fear. Russ dragged me into the moonlight and the world smelled clean again.
I heard the guards shouting behind us. Russ didn’t even look back. His confidence was louder than their boots.
Sometimes I swear I can still feel the shackles, but then I remember the moment Russ snapped them.
Russ told me my name matters. I’m still learning how to say it without whispering.
I used to think no one would risk their life for someone like me. Then Russ proved me wrong.
Anidani’s dungeon was meant to break me. Russ broke it instead.
Freedom is sweet, but seeing the pasha’s walls fade behind us was the sweetest moment of my life.
The other prisoners cheered when Russ burst in. I think he freed more hope that night than people.
I used to whisper prayers for rescue. Russ answered with steel and a grin.
I still don’t understand why he saved me, but I’ll spend my life proving he was right to.
Anidani’s men said no one escapes his dungeon. They should meet Russ.

value.0: This imposing guard looks after the vulnerable folk of the Refuge with a burning conviction.
Armor dedicated to the Full Moon Chainbreakers
Khopeshes resemble a cross between a Longsword and a Scimitar... they have a nasty swipe to them.
A True Strike dagger is perfectly balanced and thanks to its serrated edge can inflict lacerations that often take a while to heal.

Value.value: I stand watch so others can sleep without chains rattling in their dreams.
I train every morning until my hands ache. Freedom demands strength.
The Dock Ward whispers about us. Good. Let them see what courage sounds like.
We do not raise our weapons for revenge. We raise them so no one else suffers what we did.
When a new refugee steps through our doors, it reminds me why I took this oath.
Slavers hide in shadows now. Funny how justice changes the landscape.
I have no noble blood, no fancy title. Just a promise to protect those who cannot fight.
Russ told me once that courage is a habit. I practice it every day.
If battle comes, I will stand on the front line. My life belongs to the moon and the free.
Russ says freedom is worth dying for. I plan on living for it instead.
Every slaver we stop is one more soul saved from the dark. That is enough for me.
I patrol with pride. Not many can say they guard hope itself.
Some call us rebels. I call us protectors with sharper ideals than their blades.
My armor is dented, my spear is chipped, but my will is iron.
Slavers run when they see our sigil. Good. Let fear do half our work.
The refuge has children now. That alone is reason enough to fight.
Russ leads with conviction. Makes you want to follow him straight through a wall.
I used to be afraid. Now I make the ones who spread fear tremble.
They say we are outlaws. The law should be ashamed of itself then.
If the guards come for us, they’ll find we stand together. Hard to break a chain linked by choice.

Descended from crocodiles imported centuries ago from the Shining South as exotic pets or temple guardians, these creatures have long since adapted to the fetid, labyrinthine waterways beneath the city.



Over generations, Calimshan Crocodiles have evolved to thrive in total darkness and polluted waters. Their scales are mottled with grime and algae, granting them near-perfect camouflage against the slick stone tunnels. Their eyes gleam faintly yellow or red, a reflection of their low-light vision adapted to the subterranean gloom. Adults can reach lengths of 15 to 20 feet, with the largest specimens rumored to rival small boats in size.

The Calimshan Gharials are a rare and highly dangerous species of reptile that inhabit the deepest reaches of Calimport’s ancient sewer network. Believed to have descended from gharials brought from the jungles of Chult or the Lake of Steam for temple menageries, these creatures have evolved far beyond their surface-dwelling kin. Centuries of isolation and exposure to alchemical runoff, magic residue, and refuse have turned them into predators of uncanny perception and ferocity.

Value.value: The Chainbreakers crack the prison walls, we crack the vaults. Beautiful partnership, really.
Guards are too busy chasing the Chainbreakers to notice me climbing their rafters. Bless their confusion
I help where I can. Sometimes that means picking a lock for a prisoner. Sometimes it means picking a lock for myself.
The Chainbreakers handle the noble cause. I handle the noble jewels.
Freedom isn’t easy. It’s confusing, messy, frightening. But it’s right.
You’d be amazed how many valuables people leave lying around during a riot. Almost rude not to take them.
The Guild doesn’t mind me working with the Chainbreakers. As long as the loot flows uphill.
Freedom’s important, sure. But have you seen the inside of Anidani’s wine cellar? Life-changing.
When the moon rises and the chains fall, I’ll be there. Probably behind everyone else, stuffing loot into a sack.
Russ frees the people, I free the valuables. Everyone wins. Well, except the guards.
When the explosions start, that’s my cue to grab whatever isn’t nailed down. Sometimes even that.
I’m not in it for the ideals. I’m in it for the contents of the treasury room.
The slavers scream, the Chainbreakers cheer, and I slip off with armfuls of shiny justice.
The Guild says opportunity waits for no one. The Chainbreakers say freedom waits for no one. I say let’s do both at once.
Chaos is the best cover a thief could ask for. Good thing the Chainbreakers have chaos on tap.
I tell Russ I’m helping the cause. He tells me to stop stealing the cause’s pocket money.
Crept through three cells and two guardrooms last week. Didn’t find prisoners, but found a lovely gold bracelet.
The Guild loves the Chainbreakers. Not for politics. For the distraction value.
People act like stealing during a rescue is immoral. I say I’m multitasking.
Once snatched a ledger right under a slaver’s nose while Russ was shouting freedom slogans. Inspirational stuff.

I still wake up expecting the whip. Then I remember I’m free, and the fear turns into breath again.
I stitched clothes for my masters. Now I stitch banners for the Full Moon. Feels better in my hands.
A warm meal still surprises me. I hope that feeling never fades.
I owe the Chainbreakers everything. One day, I’ll repay them with more than gratitude.
Freedom isn’t easy. It’s confusing, messy, frightening. But it’s right.
The refuge smells of sweat and stew and hope. A better scent than any perfume I knew.
I’m still scared the guards will drag me back. But each day that fear shrinks a little.
There will come a time when I’m not an ex-slave anymore. Just a person. I look forward to that.
Another caravan in from Memnon... prices’ll drop for a tenday, mark my words.
The Chainbreakers didn’t just save my life. They gave it back to me.
